<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">
  <teiHeader>
    <fileDesc>
      <titleStmt>
        <title xml:lang="ta"><term xml:lang="en">Canto 3:</term> malarvaṉampukkakātai</title>
        <title type="sub">The Canto in which [Maṇimēkalai and Cutamati] Enter the Flower Grove (171
          lines)</title>
      </titleStmt>
      <publicationStmt>
        <p />
      </publicationStmt>
      <sourceDesc>
        <msDesc xml:lang="en">
          <msIdentifier>
          </msIdentifier>
          <msContents>
            <summary>
              <p>3.1-10 (10 lines) Maṇimēkalai has an understanding of Cause and Effect when she
                hears the story of her parents' suffering. She weeps, and her tears wet her garland. </p>

              <p>3.11-15 (5 lines) Mātavi sees that Maṇimēkalai's tears have spoilt her garland, and
                sends her to fetch new flowers to make a new one.</p>

              <p>3.16-25 (10 lines) Cutamati intervenes: Maṇimēkalai should not go alone, since her
                beauty while weeping will attract the unwanted attentions of men.</p>


              <p>2.33-36 Vayantamālai tells Mātavi that to avoid shaming gossip she must give up
                her asceticism.</p>

              <p>2.37-41 Mātavi replies that since losing her lover Kōvalaṉ she has renounced shame.</p>

              <p>2.42-48 Mātavi lists the options open to widows: spontaneous death, the pyre, or
                penance.</p>

              <p>2.49-55b Mātavi cites Kaṇṇaki as a paragon of female virtue. </p>

              <p>2.55c -57 Mātavi states her wish that Maṇimēkalai, who is Kaṇṇaki's daughter (by
                marriage), renounce the courtesan life and become a nun.</p>

              <p>2.58-69 Mātavi recounts how, after the death of Kōvalaṉ, she went to a Buddhist
                teacher, Aṟavaṇa for instruction.</p>

              <p>2.70-75 Mātavi concludes her speech to Vayantamālai with a request to report her
                decision to Cittirāpati and the other women. Having failed to convince Mātavi,
                Vayantamālai returns in despair to Cittirāpati.</p>


            </summary>
          </msContents>
        </msDesc>
      </sourceDesc>
    </fileDesc>
